# Page Color System

Every page (home, about, contact, services, contracting, each project) defines
exactly **two colors** in its markdown frontmatter: `bg` and `fg`. That's the
whole palette for that page, no third color.

**Dark mode is not "make it black."** The toggle swaps which of the two colors
is the background and which is the text:

```ts
const bg = isDark ? page.fg : page.bg;
const fg = isDark ? page.bg : page.fg;
```

This is the pattern already used in `ProjectView.tsx` and `ServicesView.tsx`.
Any new page view should follow it rather than introducing a separate
dark-mode color pair.

## If a section needs to visually stand out

Don't hardcode a third color or reach for the raw, unswapped
`page.bg`/`page.fg` values (that would look right in one mode and wrong in
the other). Instead, use the page's own already-swapped `bg`/`fg` in reverse
roles for that one section:

```tsx
style={{ background: fg, color: bg }}
```

This always contrasts with the rest of the page, and keeps flipping correctly
when the toggle is used, because it's built from the same two swapped values.

## Other notes

- Derive secondary treatments (dividers, borders, muted text) from `fg`/`bg`
  with a hex alpha suffix, e.g. `` `${fg}30` ``, rather than a new color.
- Jeremy is exploring using one of the two colors at partial opacity as a
  background tint. Still just two base colors per page if you do this.
